'''Alison M. Marr''' is an American mathematician and [[mathematics education|mathematics educator]]. Her research concerns [[graph theory]] and [[graph labeling]], and she is also an advocate of [[inquiry-based learning]] in mathematics. She works as a professor of mathematics and computer science at [[Southwestern University]] in [[Texas]].{{r|swfac}}
==Education and career== Marr graduated from [[Murray State University]] in 2002, and earned a master's degree in mathematics at [[Texas A&M University]] in 2004.{{r|cv}} She completed her Ph.D. in 2007 at [[Southern Illinois University]]; her dissertation, ''Labelings of Directed Graphs'', was supervised by Walter D. Wallis.{{r|cv|mgp}}
She has been a member of the mathematics faculty at Southwestern University since 2007.{{r|cv}} She was department chair for 2015–2018. Beyond mathematics, her teaching at Southwestern has included a freshman seminar on [[game show|television game shows]].{{r|tv}}
==Contributions== ===Inquiry-based learning=== Marr is an advocate of [[inquiry-based learning]] in mathematics, a style of teaching through student research rather than through presentation of packaged solutions that is closely related to the [[Moore method]]. She was one of the founding officers of the inquiry-based learning special interest group of the [[Mathematical Association of America]], which was established in 2016.{{r|ibl}} She is an editor of the ''Journal of Inquiry-Based Learning in Mathematics'',{{r|jiblm}} and serves on the board of directors of the Initiative for Mathematics Learning By Inquiry.{{r|mli}}
===Graph theory=== With Walter Wallis, Marr is the author of a book on [[magic graph]]s and graph labeling, ''Magic Graphs'' (2nd ed., Springer, 2013).{{r|magic}} She spoke about magic graph labelings as an invited speaker at the Midwest Conference on Combinatorics, Cryptography, and Computing in 2011.{{r|mwc4}}
